# Engineering Assumptions

> **Important:** Every numeric value in this document and in
> `data/scenarios/base_scenario.json` and `routes.csv` is a
> synthetic engineering assumption created for software verification
> and comparative experiments. None of these values are derived from
> or intended to represent an actual operating mine.

## Baseline Scenario (Section 6.2)

| Parameter | Value | Interpretation |
|---|---|---|
| Shift duration | 480 minutes | One 8-hour simulated shift. |
| Warm-up period | 30 minutes | Excludes early transient data from KPI reporting. |
| Trucks | 6 | Homogeneous initial fleet. |
| Truck capacity | 95 t nominal | Payload sampled between 88 and 100 t. |
| Shovels | 2 | Two competing loading resources. |
| Dumps | 2 | Two feasible destinations. |
| Shovel 1 loading | Triangular(3.5, 4.5, 6.0) min | Min, mode, max. |
| Shovel 2 loading | Triangular(4.0, 5.0, 6.5) min | Slightly slower baseline shovel. |
| Dump 1 service | Triangular(0.8, 1.2, 2.0) min | Dumping or crusher tip time. |
| Dump 2 service | Triangular(1.0, 1.5, 2.4) min | Slightly slower second dump. |
| Initial estimator α | 0.20 | EWMA learning rate. |
| Replications | 20 | Minimum comparison experiment. |
| Base random seed | 20260715 | Reproducibility. |

## Route Assumptions (Section 6.3)

Mean traveT_minutes = (distance_km / speed_kph) * 60

A stochastic multiplier from `Triangular(0.88, 1.00, 1.18)` is applied
to represent normal variability in road conditions and operator behavior.

